  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is an exclusive use area in a Brisbane unit or townhouse?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "An exclusive use area is a portion of the body corporate's common property that a particular lot has the legal right to use to the exclusion of all other lots in the scheme. Common examples in Brisbane units include allocated car parks, storage cages, courtyards, gardens, balconies that sit on common property, and rooftop terraces. The right is granted by an exclusive use by-law in the scheme's community management statement under the Body Corporate and Community Management Act 1997 (Qld). The area remains part of the common property and is still owned by the body corporate, but the named lot owner has the sole right to use it for the term specified in the by-law."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does exclusive use transfer to the buyer when I sell my Brisbane unit?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes, an exclusive use right granted by a by-law in the community management statement is attached to the lot, not to the individual owner. When the lot is sold, the exclusive use right transfers automatically to the new owner with the lot. The buyer does not need a separate document of transfer for the right itself. The exception is where exclusive use has only been granted informally, by long-standing agreement between owners or by an entry in committee minutes rather than the CMS. In that case the right is not enforceable on a new owner and the seller should not represent it as guaranteed."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What do I need to disclose about exclusive use areas when selling my Brisbane unit?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Under the Queensland seller disclosure regime, the seller must provide a disclosure statement before contract that includes the community management statement and details of any exclusive use by-laws affecting the lot. Buyers and their solicitors will also order a body corporate records search to confirm exactly which areas are exclusive use, what the maintenance arrangements are, and whether any conditions or contributions apply. Sellers should confirm the specific car park numbers, storage cage numbers, and any garden or courtyard areas attached to their lot before listing, so the marketing matches what the by-laws actually grant."
      }
    }
  ]
};
